.9,"Integration":0.09,"System":0.01,"Agentic":0,"Workflow":0}},{"behavior_id":3,"description":"A CSV file with 500,000 rows completes processing within the configured timeout without running out of memory.","minimum_level":"System","justification":"Real failure depends on runtime characteristics (memory pressure, GC behavior, wall-clock timeout) that mocks hide. This is REAL-INFRA: needs actual process execution with realistic data volume and timeout enforcement. Integration with small in-process fakes can pass while production still OOMs or times out.","test_description":"Execute the pipeline as a real process against a 500k-row fixture under production-like memory/time limits; assert completion before configured timeout and peak memory below threshold, with successful end-state counts.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.01,"Integration":0.12,"System":0.87,"Agentic":0,"Workflow":0}},{"behavior_id":4,"description":"When the S3 bucket returns a transient 503 error, the pipeline retries with exponential backoff rather than failing the entire batch.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"Primary failure boundary is retry orchestration between S3 client adapter, retry policy, and batch controller. This can be caught with module wiring plus a deterministic stub/fake returning 503 then success; exponential schedule can be asserted with fake clock. Rejected higher level (System) because behavior text targets retry policy semantics, not real network pathologies or OS-level socket behavior.","test_description":"Wire pipeline with a stubbed S3 adapter that returns 503 for first N calls then success; verify retry count, exponential backoff intervals, and that batch continues to completion instead of terminal failure.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.05,"Integration":0.7,"System":0.25,"Agentic":0,"Workflow":0}},{"behavior_id":5,"description":"Rows successfully written to